  <example>
    <statement>
        <p>
        After your group activity, let's see how we can measure the steepness more precisely. For example, consider a ramp that you measured earlier.
        </p>
        <p>
        Suppose one ramp rises <m>1.2 m</m> over a horizontal distance of <m>4 m</m>. To express its steepness numerically, we use the concept of the gradient, often calculated as:
        </p>
        <p>
        <m> \text{Gradient (m)} = \frac{\text{Rise}}{\text{Run}} </m>
        </p>
        <p>
        Thus, for this ramp: 
        </p>
        <p>
        <m> m = \frac{1.2}{4} = 0.3 </m>
        </p>
        <p>
        This numerical value, <m>0.3</m>, indicates that for every 1 metre along the ramp, the height increases by 0.3 m.
        </p>
    </statement>
  </example>
</worksheet>

<conclusion>
    <p>
      <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway:}</m> The gradient gives a numerical value to the concept of steepness, allowing us to compare different slopes and understand their practical implications for safety, accessibility, and design.
    </p>
  </conclusion>
